16 years ago today I was diagnosed with Leukemia. Sometimes I can be a little facetious when talking about it, but the truth is that when I was diagnosed, we didn’t know what my future would hold or how long I would live. I got really sick, things got ugly, people were scared and confused. But there was something burning inside of me that wouldn’t stop, even in my darkest hour. I wasn’t scared to die. I wanted to LIVE.

While my prognosis is much brighter now, there are still many unknowns. No matter what, that fire for life burns on. What an unbelievable ride this journey is, and thank you all of being a part of it. Cheers! ❤️🥂

#CML #leukemia #cancer #survivor

My childhood gymnastics coach, Tammy, was the queen of “handstands around the world”, always living life fully and having a blast doing it. She was fierce, FUN, hard when she needed to be, soft when she needed to be, TOUGH AS NAILS and a true all around badass and incredible human. Sadly she was taken too soon by breast cancer. I wasn’t able to attend her memorial this week, so here’s to you, Tammy. May we all live life with fierce passion and do the very best we can with the hands we’re dealt.🤸🏻❤️

One of the toughest things about having a non-traditional schedule (including a lot of travel) is trying to stay healthy and fit. Even with a “routine”, it can be challenging.

My NUMBER ONE RULE, no matter where in the world I am or what I’m doing is to stretch. Every. Day. I swear there have been times when stretching alone has kept me both sane and toned while in demanding work-streaks. In privacy (or with dogs, lots of dogs) is ideal, but I’ll stretch anywhere. Yes - I am the girl stretching at the airport 😁 And I love it! You can do it no matter what your energy level, so it’s especially important for times when you can’t drag yourself to the gym.

I have zero scientific evidence to back this up, but it has made a huge difference in my life. Put on some jams (ideally funky beats) and do it! 🧘🏼‍♀️🤸🏼‍♀️

Ok first of all, this was crazy fun. Being on the water again gave me LIFE!! Obviously it was insanely cold, but the wildest part was that it was so glassy you couldn’t see where the water ended and the ice began. When you stopped the water moving under the thin layer of ice made an insane sound. It was sort of eerie actually.

Second, before anyone freaks out, despite what it sounds like going through the ice, there was zero damage done to the board (still wouldn’t recommend it, but pretty crazy). Super impressed with how durable these boards are. Anyway, I will 100% be milking summer as long as humanly possible. 🏄🏼‍♀️❄️
